        "name": "",
        "username": "Wopfi",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/wopfi/{size}/1243_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-07-04T10:36:16.295Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote group-top_contributors\" data-username=\"rassilon1963\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"70210\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/rassilon1963/48/31625_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> rassilon1963:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>this sounds to me like an OS feature, not a Signal feature</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>In theory yes, but I don‚Äôt think that Windows will implement a feature to deactivate their protection of DRM content, even if it‚Äôs only for a short time.</p>\n<p>After all, this is not a feature made to help users (like Signal is using it) but for companies to protect them from the bad users stealing their IP by screenshotting it ;)</p>\n<p>Does anyone with experience in Windows DRM know if the DRM flag in the App can be turned off temporarily?</p>",
